# Silicon Valley Trail

An Oregon Trail-inspired startup survival game where a scrappy team travels from San Jose to San Francisco, managing resources, responding to events, and adapting to real-world conditions like weather.

## Overview

In **Silicon Valley Trail**, the player leads a startup team on a journey through major Silicon Valley cities. Each turn represents a day. The player must make strategic decisions, manage limited resources, and survive random and conditional events to reach the final destination.

The game combines:
- resource management
- turn-based decision making
- semi-random city events
- external API integration
- persistent game state

---

## Quick Start

### 1. Clone the repository

```bash
git clone <your-repo-url>
cd silicon-valley-trail

```


2. Create and activate a virtual environment 

```bash
# mac 
python3 -m venv venv
source venv/bin/activate

# windows 
python -m venv venv
venv\Scripts\activate

3. install dependencies 
```bash
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

4. set up environment variables 

- create .env file in project root

```bash
FLASK_APP=run.py
FLASK_ENV=development # deprecated = should be 1
OPENWEATHER_API_KEY=your_api_key_here
USE_MOCK_WEATHER=false # set true when using mock true (implementation not complete)
```

5. Initialize the database 
```bash
python data/seed_data.py
```

6. Start server 
```bash 
python run.py
```

#### API Key Set up
This project uses the OpenWeather API to influence gameplay through weather-based conditions and events.

OpenWeather Setup
1. Create an account 
2. Generate an API key 
3. Add it to your .env file 
   ```bash
   OPENWEATHER_API_KEY=your_api_key_here
   ```
Notes
	•	Do not hardcode API keys in source files
	•	Make sure .env is included in .gitignore
	•	In development or testing, you can use mock responses instead of real API calls

### Architecture Overview 
This project follows a modular Flask architecture with separation of concerns using App Factory 

Main layers

Routes / Controllers
	•	Handle HTTP requests
	•	Process form input
	•	Call service-layer functions
	•	Render templates or redirect

Services
	•	Contain business logic
	•	Update game state
	•	Trigger events
	•	Fetch weather data
	•	Evaluate win/loss conditions

Models
	•	Define persistent database entities using SQLAlchemy
	•	Store game session and location data

Templates
	•	Render UI with Jinja
	•	Display resources, events, weather, and progress

Data / Mock Data
	•	Provide seed locations
	•	Store event definitions
	•	Support offline development and testing

Dependencies 
can be found in requirements.txt

Key dependencies used and purpose 
	•	Flask: web framework
	•	Flask-SQLAlchemy: ORM and database interaction
	•	Flask-Migrate: database migrations
	•	python-dotenv: environment variable loading
	•	requests: API calls to OpenWeather
	•	pytest: testing framework
	•	pytest-mock: mocking external dependencies in tests

Running Tests

```bash
pytest 
pytest tests/test_service.py # run specific test
pytest -v # run verbose output 


Tradeoffs 

- used SQLite instead of PostgreSQL/MySQL
- used Jinja templates instead of fronted framework like React
- kept progression linear across cities for easier balancing 